The expression is: \[ \sqrt{\frac{\log (n^2) - (\log n)^2}{\log n - 3}} \] For the square root to be real, the expression inside must be non-negative: \[ \frac{\log (n^2) - (\log n)^2}{\log n - 3} \geq 0 \] Simplify the numerator: \[ \log (n^2) = 2 \log n \] Thus, the numerator becomes: \[ 2 \log n - (\log n)^2 = - (\log n)^2 + 2 \log n = - (\log n)(\log n - 2) \] Let \( x = \log n \), so the expression becomes: \[ \frac{-x(x - 2)}{x - 3} \geq 0 \] We analyze the inequality: \[ \frac{-x(x - 2)}{x - 3} \geq 0 \] This simplifies to: \[ \frac{x(x - 2)}{x - 3} \leq 0 \] The critical points are \( x = 0 \), \( x = 2 \), and \( x = 3 \). Testing intervals around these points, we find the solution set for \( x \) is: \[ 0 < x < 2 \quad \text{or} \quad 2 < x < 3 \] Since \( x = \log n \) and \( n \) must be an integer greater than 0, we convert back to \( n \): \[ 10^0 < n < 10^2 \quad \text{or} \quad 10^2 < n < 10^3 \] Thus: \[ 1 < n < 100 \quad \text{or} \quad 100 < n < 1000 \] Since \( n \) must be an integer, the valid values are \( n = 101, 102, \ldots, 999 \).
